Patches break existing systems.  Call for ownership went unanswered.  Open comments on code reviews.
15 seconds seems ludicrously high for that.  I would expect something like 10-100ms as a reload time.

The author of service-config-manager designs a 15s window for incoming changes (each DBus set is considered as one change), changes submitted in the following 15s from the first change will be merged and applied together. He says decreasing the 15s window time will causes multiple service restarts and may cause loss of data.
Acked in another patch
Please use the common types for these.  Don't add your own type.
Done
Please split this funciton up, it goes 8 scopes deep in some places.
After switched to GetManagedObjects, it's hard to split it up perfectly I think. Please tell me if you got any better ideas.
Left comments above.
Done
Please don't capture by reference like this.  It tends to have lifetime issues, and in this case, I suspect you can just use a json path name.
Done
flat_map is not used in this file.
Done
I suspect this change isn't needed, you just need to change the underlying path build mechanisms to use sdbusplus::mesage::object_path operator/ and .filename() which will escape these automatically.

Using sdbusplus::mesage::object_path operator/ and .filename() brings extra cost I think, and this is only used in getNetworkData() of network_protocol.hpp. And in previous implementation, this is also hardcoded in PATCH handler https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/5f2b84ee090bb9d361de9c294aa85cecf3962c11/redfish-core/lib/network_protocol.hpp#L462

It is also hardcoded in PATCH handler in my patch, should I make it a constexpr instead?

Unfortunately, service-config-manager does not use sdbusplus to encode path, instead, it only replaces some specific characters. Meaning that it is not in sdbusplus-encodeable format.

https://github.com/openbmc/service-config-manager/blob/ef5ceced0bee522da0fce5c759b9b733298d82bd/src/main.cpp#L135
Seems like something we need to fix then.
Fixed in a merged patch

this block can be abstracted to a method.
Return in a method brings more effort as it requires checking the return value of that method to decide whether return here or continue the loop.

I'm not sure what you're meaning by "more effort".  Yes, there's one extra branch, but it breaks up the code in such a way that it's easier to review.  We've done that pattern elsewhere.  Can you elaborate on what you mean?
Yes, the extra branch. Since it is okay, I've separated it to a new function.

?  Why would we set it to null if the service doesn't exist?  That seems incorrect?

Redfish spec says this property is nullable. https://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP2046_2021.4.html#managernetworkprotocol-180

And in our current implementation, Port is null when the service does not exist or is disabled.
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/456cd875f3c56b45605d8a017e91d810876a035c/redfish-core/lib/network_protocol.hpp#L184

But for the unexist "HTTP" service, the Port is set to 0. It's also okay as 0 is an invalid port.
https://github.com/openbmc/bmcweb/blob/456cd875f3c56b45605d8a017e91d810876a035c/redfish-core/lib/network_protocol.hpp#L124

I have no idea of which one is preferred. Any suggestions will be appreciated.
I don't see any flat_map uses here.
